<doc id="26215" wikidata="Q927051" url="?curid=26215" title="Riemann mapping theorem">
<text>In complex analysis, the Riemann mapping theorem states that if formula_1 is a non-empty simply connected open subset of the complex number plane formula_2 which is not all of formula_2, then there exists a biholomorphic mapping formula_4 (i.e. a bijective holomorphic mapping whose inverse is also holomorphic) from formula_1 onto the open unit disk 
:formula_6

This mapping is known as a Riemann mapping.

Intuitively, the condition that formula_1 be simply connected means that formula_1 does not contain any “holes”. The fact that formula_4 is biholomorphic implies that it is a conformal map and therefore angle-preserving. Such a map may be interpreted as preserving the shape of any sufficiently small figure, while possibly rotating and scaling (but not reflecting) it.

Henri Poincaré proved that the map formula_4 is unique up to rotation and recentering: if formula_11 is an element of formula_1 and formula_13 is an arbitrary angle, then there exists precisely one &quot;f&quot; as above such that formula_14 and such that the argument of the derivative of formula_4 at the point formula_11 is equal to formula_13. This is an easy consequence of the Schwarz lemma.

As a corollary of the theorem, any two simply connected open subsets of the Riemann sphere which both lack at least two points of the sphere can be conformally mapped into each other.

==History==
The theorem was stated (under the assumption that the boundary of formula_1 is piecewise smooth) by Bernhard Riemann in 1851 in his PhD thesis. Lars Ahlfors wrote once, concerning the original formulation of the theorem, that it was “ultimately formulated in terms which would defy any attempt of proof, even with modern methods”. Riemann&#x27;s flawed proof depended on the Dirichlet principle (which was named by Riemann himself), which was considered sound at the time. However, Karl Weierstrass found that this principle was not universally valid. Later, David Hilbert was able to prove that, to a large extent, the Dirichlet principle is valid under the hypothesis that Riemann was working with. However, in order to be valid, the Dirichlet principle needs certain hypotheses concerning the boundary of formula_1 (namely, that it is a Jordan curve) which are not valid for simply connected domains in general.

The first rigorous proof of the theorem was given by William Fogg Osgood in 1900. He proved the existence of Green&#x27;s function on arbitrary simply connected domains other than formula_2 itself; this established the Riemann mapping theorem.

Constantin Carathéodory gave another proof of the theorem in 1912, which was the first to rely purely on the methods of function theory rather than potential theory. His proof used Montel&#x27;s concept of normal families, which became the standard method of proof in textbooks. Carathéodory continued in 1913 by resolving the additional question of whether the Riemann mapping between the domains can be extended to a homeomorphism of the boundaries (see Carathéodory&#x27;s theorem).

Carathéodory&#x27;s proof used Riemann surfaces and it was simplified by Paul Koebe two years later in a way that did not require them. Another proof, due to Lipót Fejér and to Frigyes Riesz, was published in 1922 and it was rather shorter than the previous ones. In this proof, like in Riemann&#x27;s proof, the desired mapping was obtained as the solution of an extremal problem. The Fejér–Riesz proof was further simplified by Alexander Ostrowski and by Carathéodory.

==Importance==
The following points detail the uniqueness and power of the Riemann mapping theorem:

* Even relatively simple Riemann mappings (for example a map from the interior of a circle to the interior of a square) have no explicit formula using only elementary functions.
* Simply connected open sets in the plane can be highly complicated, for instance, the boundary can be a nowhere-differentiable fractal curve of infinite length, even if the set itself is bounded. One such example is the Koch curve. The fact that such a set can be mapped in an &quot;angle-preserving&quot; manner to the nice and regular unit disc seems counter-intuitive.
* The analog of the Riemann mapping theorem for more complicated domains is not true. The next simplest case is of doubly connected domains (domains with a single hole). Any doubly connected domain except for the punctured disk and the punctured plane is conformally equivalent to some annulus formula_21 with formula_22, however there are no conformal maps between annuli except inversion and multiplication by constants so the annulus formula_23 is not conformally equivalent to the annulus formula_24 (as can be proven using extremal length).
* The analogue of the Riemann mapping theorem in three or more real dimensions is not true. The family of conformal maps in three dimensions is very poor, and essentially contains only Möbius transformations (see Liouville&#x27;s theorem).
* Even if arbitrary homeomorphisms in higher dimensions are permitted, contractible manifolds can be found that are not homeomorphic to the ball (e.g., the Whitehead continuum).
* The analogue of the Riemann mapping theorem in several complex variables is also not true. In formula_25 (formula_26), the ball and polydisk are both simply connected, but there is no biholomorphic map between them.

== Proof via normal families ==
=== Simple connectivity ===

Theorem. For an open domain formula_27 the following conditions are equivalent:

# formula_28 is simply connected;
# the integral of every holomorphic function formula_4 around a closed piecewise smooth curve in formula_28 vanishes;
# every holomorphic function in formula_28 is the derivative of a holomorphic function; 
# every nowhere-vanishing holomorphic function formula_4 on formula_28 has a holomorphic logarithm;
# every nowhere-vanishing holomorphic function formula_34 on formula_28 has a holomorphic square root;
# for any formula_36, the winding number of formula_37 for any piecewise smooth closed curve in formula_28 is formula_39;
# the complement of formula_28 in the extended complex plane formula_41 is connected.

(1) ⇒ (2) because any continuous closed curve, with base point formula_42, can be continuously deformed to the constant curve formula_43. So the line integral of formula_44 over the curve is formula_39.

(2) ⇒ (3) because the integral over any piecewise smooth path formula_46 from formula_43 to formula_48 can be used to define a primitive.

(3) ⇒ (4) by integrating formula_49 along formula_46 from formula_43 to formula_52 to give a branch of the logarithm.

(4) ⇒ (5) by taking the square root as formula_53 where formula_4 is a holomorphic choice of logarithm.

(5) ⇒ (6) because if formula_46 is a piecewise closed curve and formula_56 are successive square roots of formula_57 for formula_37 outside formula_28, then the winding number of formula_60 about formula_37 is formula_62 times the winding number of formula_46 about formula_39. Hence the winding number of formula_46 about formula_37 must be divisible by formula_62 for all formula_68, so it must equal formula_39.

(6) ⇒ (7) for otherwise the extended plane formula_70 can be written as the disjoint union of two open and closed sets formula_71 and formula_72 with formula_73 and formula_71 bounded. Let formula_75 be the shortest Euclidean distance between formula_71 and formula_72 and build a square grid on formula_2 with length formula_79 with a point formula_43 of formula_71 at the centre of a square. Let formula_82 be the compact set of the union of all squares with distance formula_83 from formula_71. Then formula_85 and formula_86 does not meet formula_71 or formula_72: it consists of finitely many horizontal and vertical segments in formula_28 forming a finite number of closed rectangular paths formula_90. Taking formula_91 to be all the squares covering formula_71, then formula_93 equals the sum of the winding numbers of formula_91 
over formula_43, thus giving formula_96. On the other hand the sum of the winding numbers of formula_97 about formula_43 equals formula_96. Hence the winding number of at least one of the formula_97 about formula_43 is non-zero.

(7) ⇒ (1) This is a purely topological argument. Let formula_46 be a piecewise smooth closed curve based at formula_103. By approximation γ is in the same homotopy class as a rectangular path on the square grid of length formula_75 based at formula_11; such a rectangular path is determined by a succession of formula_106 consecutive directed vertical and horizontal sides. By induction on formula_106, such a path can be deformed to a constant path at a corner of the grid. If the path intersects at a point formula_108, then it breaks up into two rectangular paths of length formula_109, and thus can be deformed to the constant path at formula_108 by the induction hypothesis and elementary properties of the fundamental group. The reasoning follows a &quot;northeast argument&quot;: in the non self-intersecting path there will be a corner formula_11 with largest real part (easterly) and then amongst those one with largest imaginary part (northerly). Reversing direction if need be, the path go from formula_112 to formula_11 and then to formula_114 for formula_115 and then goes leftwards to formula_116. Let formula_117 be the open rectangle with these vertices. The winding number of the path is formula_39 for points to the right of the vertical segment from formula_11 to formula_120 and formula_121 for points to the right; and hence inside formula_117. Since the winding number is formula_39 off formula_28, formula_117 lies in formula_28. If formula_48 is a point of the path, it must lie in formula_28; if formula_48 is on formula_130 but not on the path, by continuity the winding number of the path about formula_48 is formula_121, so formula_48 must also lie in formula_28. Hence formula_135. But in this case the path can be deformed by replacing the three sides of the rectangle by the fourth, resulting in two less sides (with self-intersections permitted).

=== Riemann mapping theorem ===

*Weierstrass&#x27; convergence theorem. The uniform limit on compacta of a sequence of holomorphic functions is holomorphic; similarly for derivatives.
::This is an immediate consequence of Morera&#x27;s theorem for the first statement. Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula gives a formula for the derivatives which can be used to check that the derivatives also converge uniformly on compacta.

*Hurwitz&#x27;s theorem. If a sequence of nowhere-vanishing holomorphic functions on an open domain has a uniform limit on compacta, then either the limit is identically zero or the limit is nowhere-vanishing. If a sequence of univalent holomorphic functions on an open domain has a uniform limit on compacta, then either the limit is constant or the limit is univalent.
::If the limit function is non-zero, then its zeros have to be isolated. Zeros with multiplicities can be counted by the winding number formula_136 for a holomorphic function formula_34. Hence winding numbers are continuous under uniform limits, so that if each function in the sequence has no zeros nor can the limit. For the second statement suppose that formula_138 and set formula_139. These are nowhere-vanishing on a disk but formula_140 vanishes at formula_141, so formula_34 must vanish identically.

Definitions. A family formula_143 of holomorphic functions on an open domain is said to be &quot;normal&quot; if any sequence of functions in formula_143 has a subsequence that converges to a holomorphic function uniformly on compacta. 
A family formula_143 is &quot;compact&quot; if whenever a sequence formula_56 lies in formula_143 and converges uniformly to formula_4 on compacta, then formula_4 also lies in formula_143. A family formula_143 is said to be &quot;locally bounded&quot; if their functions are uniformly bounded on each compact disk. Differentiating the Cauchy integral formula, it follows that the derivatives of a locally bounded family are also locally bounded.

*Montel&#x27;s theorem. Every locally bounded family of holomorphic functions in a domain formula_28 is normal. 
::Let formula_56 be a totally bounded sequence and chose a countable dense subset formula_154 of formula_28. By locally boundedness and a &quot;diagonal argument&quot;, a subsequence can be chosen so that formula_156 is convergent at each point formula_154. It must be verified that this sequence of holomorphic functions converges on formula_28 uniformly on each compactum formula_159. Take formula_160 open with formula_161 such that the closure of formula_160 is compact and contains formula_28. Since the sequence formula_164 is locally bounded, formula_165 on formula_160. By compactness, if formula_75 is taken small enough, finitely many open disks formula_168 of radius formula_75 are required to cover formula_159 while remaining in formula_160. Since 
