::To prove existence, take formula_143 to be the family of holomorphic univalent mappings formula_4 of formula_28 into the open unit disk formula_189 with formula_190 and formula_191. It is a normal family by Montel&#x27;s theorem. By the characterization of simple-connectivity, for formula_207 there is a holomorphic branch of the square root formula_208 in formula_28. It is univalent and formula_210 for formula_211. Since formula_212 must contain a closed disk formula_213 with centre formula_214 and radius formula_215, no points of formula_216 can lie in formula_212. Let formula_218 be the unique Möbius transformation taking formula_219 onto formula_189 with the normalization formula_221 and formula_222. By construction formula_223 is in formula_143, so that formula_143 is &quot;non-empty&quot;. The method of Koebe is to use an &quot;extremal function&quot; to produce a conformal mapping solving the problem: in this situation it is often called the &quot;Ahlfors function&quot; of , after Ahlfors. Let formula_226 be the supremum of formula_227 for formula_228. Pick formula_229 with formula_230 tending to formula_231. By Montel&#x27;s theorem, passing to a subsequence if necessary, formula_56 tends to a holomorphic function formula_4 uniformly on compacta. By Hurwitz&#x27;s theorem, formula_4 is either univalent or constant. But formula_4 has formula_190 and formula_191. So formula_231 is finite, equal to formula_191 and formula_240. It remains to check that the conformal mapping formula_4 takes formula_28 &quot;onto&quot; formula_189. If not, take formula_244 in formula_245 and let formula_246 be a holomorphic square root of formula_247 on formula_28. The function formula_246 is univalent and maps formula_28 into formula_189. Let
